  "prompt": "What is indexing?",
  "response": "Indexing is a database optimization technique used to improve the speed of data retrieval operations. Here's a comprehensive overview of indexing:\n\n1. Basic Concept\n- An index is a data structure that allows faster retrieval of records from a database table\n- It works similar to a book's index, providing quick access to specific data\n\n2. How Indexing Works\n- Creates a separate structure that stores a copy of selected columns\n- Provides a faster way to look up data without scanning the entire table\n- Uses a data structure like B-tree or hash table to organize data\n\n3. Types of Indexes\n- Single-column index\n- Composite index (multiple columns)\n- Unique index\n- Clustered index\n- Non-clustered index\n- Partial index\n- Full-text index\n\n4. Benefits\n- Faster data retrieval\n- Improved query performance\n- Reduced disk I/O\n- Efficient sorting and searching\n\n5. Drawbacks\n- Additional storage space required\n- Slower write operations\n- Overhead during data modifications\n\n6. When to Use Indexing\n- Large tables\n- Frequently queried columns\n- Columns used in WHERE, JOIN, and ORDER BY clauses\n\n7. Best Practices\n- Index selectively\n- Monitor and maintain indexes\n- Analyze query performance\n- Remove unused indexes",
